Part I: Machine learning (90pts)

Background¶

There are four levels of protein structure: primary, secondary, tertiary, and quaternary.

The simplest level of protein structure, primary structure, is simply the sequence of amino acids in a polypeptide chain.

The next level of protein structure, secondary structure, refers to local folded structures that form within a polypeptide due to interactions between atoms of the backbone. The two most common secondary structural elements are alpha helices and beta sheets, though beta turns and omega loops occur as well.

To make it simpler, you're only required to train a binary classifier to predict secondary structure (alpha-helix vs. not alpha-helix) instead of multiclass classifier (alpha helix, beta sheet, omega loop, etc), using features derived from protein sequences (primary structure).

Dataset¶

Labels.txt¶

This file contains 3 columns:

UniProt Position    Label
A0A1C9J6A7  1   0
A0A1C9J6A7  2   0
A0A1C9J6A7  3   0
...

  • Uniprot ID: Uniprot ID for a given protein.

  • Position: The position of the amino acid (1-based) in a given protein.

  • Label: 0 indicates that the amino acid in this position has either unknown structure or is known not to form an alpha-helix, while 1 indicates that the position is known to form an alpha-helix.

You can regard each row as a sample, e.g., the label for the first sample (the first amino acid of the protein A0A1C9J6A7) is 0.

UniProt2Seq.txt¶

This file contains 3 columns:

UniProt Position    AA
A0R4Q6  1   M
A0R4Q6  2   T
A0R4Q6  3   Q
...

  • Uniprot ID: Uniprot ID for a given protein.

  • Position: The position of the amino acid (1-based) in a given protein.

  • Amino Acid: 1-letter abbreviations for amino acids.

The sequence information of all proteins in Labels.txt file can be found in UniProt2Seq.txt file.

Expasy_AA_Scales.txt¶

This file contains 57 predefined amino acid scales from the literature. An amino acid scale is defined by a numerical value assigned to each type of amino acid. These scales include hydrophobicity or hydrophilicity scales, the secondary structure conformational parameters scales, and many other scales based on different chemical and physical properties of the amino acids.

  • Amino Acid: 1-letter abbreviations for amino acids.

  • Other columns: each column refers to one amino acid scale.

Feature engineering (20pts)¶

You may directly use the features from Expasy_AA_Scales.txt. You may take into account the sequence context surrounding a given position. For instance, within a 2X-window surrounding a position (pos-X, pos+X), what is the average value on one of the amino acid scales (blurring the feature)? It may also make sense to rank these features to figure out what positions have the highest values relative to the protein they belong in. You may also come up with other informative features.

You need to do some data exploration. Some things you may want to consider...

  • How correlated are different features to one another? Can you weed out redundant features?

  • How correlated is each feature with the label (e.g., violin plot, boxplot, etc)?

  • ...

A rough algorithm for VERY GREEDY (i.e. not optimal) feature selection:

  • Step 1: Start with an emtpy bag of features.

  • Step 2: Train your classifier using each of the candidate features alone (or in combination with the current feature bag).

  • Step 3: Select the single feature that gives the best performance and add it to the feature bag.

  • Step 4: Repeat steps 2 and 3 until desired number of features are selected or the addition of new features no longer considerably increases performance.

  • Step 5: Use final selection of features for your final classifier.

You can include a plot that shows how your performance changes with 1 to n features (should be a curve that flattens out at the top).

Note: These are just some suggestions. You're NOT required to do all the things mentioned above. You'll get full credits as long as you're able to do feature engineering in a reasonable way and clearly explain why you select what features.
